Adaptive Composite Cold Dark Matter (ACCDM)

A Proposed Galaxy-Scale Extension to ΛCDM

Author: Mina Moussa
Date: May 2026


---

Abstract

Adaptive Composite Cold Dark Matter (ACCDM) is a speculative extension to the standard ΛCDM cosmological framework. Rather than replacing Cold Dark Matter (CDM), ACCDM proposes that dark matter consists of composite hidden-sector structures capable of emergent adaptive behaviour inside mature galaxies while remaining effectively standard cold dark matter during early cosmological evolution.

The framework aims to preserve the large-scale successes of ΛCDM — including Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB) consistency, structure formation, and galaxy cluster behaviour — while addressing unresolved galaxy-scale tensions such as:

the core-cusp problem,

rotation-curve diversity,

baryon-dark matter coupling,

and too-big-to-fail.


The central proposal is that dark matter particles are not elementary point particles, but composite hidden-sector bound states capable of:

self-assembly,

pathway reinforcement,

adaptive relaxation,

filamentary organisation,

and coherent alignment with galactic flow geometry.


This emergent organisation may generate additional rotational support inside galaxies without modifying gravity itself.


---

1. Motivation

ΛCDM remains the dominant cosmological model because it successfully explains:

the Cosmic Microwave Background,

large-scale structure,

gravitational lensing,

galaxy cluster dynamics,

and cosmic expansion.


However, tensions remain at galactic scales:

Known Galaxy-Scale Tensions

Core-Cusp Problem

Standard CDM simulations predict dense cuspy galactic centres, while many observed galaxies show flatter density cores.

Rotation Curve Diversity

Galaxies with similar baryonic masses can display significantly different rotation curves.

Too-Big-To-Fail

Simulated large satellite halos often appear denser than observed dwarf galaxies.

Baryon–Dark Matter Coupling

Observed galaxy rotation often correlates surprisingly strongly with visible matter distribution.

These tensions suggest that dark matter may possess richer internal physics at galaxy scales than standard collisionless CDM assumes.


